          en: "Bulgakov inverts detective fiction: the Devil becomes investigator exposing human wickedness. Woland arrives in atheist Moscow and through supernatural 'experiments'—magic shows, temptations, interventions—reveals citizens' corruption, materialism, and hypocrisy. Unlike detectives who restore order, Woland exposes moral chaos the Soviet regime claims to have eliminated. His 'detection' proves that removing God didn't create virtue; Moscow's atheism masks spiritual bankruptcy. This satirical detective narrative critiques Stalinist totalitarianism: the supernatural detective reveals truths the regime suppresses. Bulgakov transforms detection from solving crimes to exposing systemic moral corruption.",
